{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.35,0.07,0.05,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96592"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with amenorrhoea over the past four months. She also reports increased anxiety, four kilograms weight loss and occasional diarrhoea over the past three months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has a fine tremor and mild exophthalmos. Neck examination reveals a diffusely enlarged thyroid gland without discrete nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) \u0026lt;0.01 mU/L (0.4-4.0), free thyroxine (T4) 32 pmol/L (9-19), and free triiodothyronine (T3) 12 pmol/L (3.0-6.5). Thyroid ultrasound shows a diffusely enlarged gland with a 1.5 cm hypoechoic mass in the left lobe. Thyroid scintigraphy demonstrates diffuse increased uptake consistent with Graves\u0027 disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe undergoes total thyroidectomy for management of her thyrotoxicosis. Histopathology of the resected thyroid reveals changes consistent with Graves\u0027 disease and an incidental 0.5 cm papillary microcarcinoma in the upper pole of the left lobe with clear margins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound neck surveillance in 12 months","Clinical surveillance","MRI neck with contrast","Completion lymph node dissection","Radioiodine ablation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has undergone total thyroidectomy for Graves\u0027 disease and was incidentally found to have a small (0.5 cm) papillary thyroid microcarcinoma. Thyroid microcarcinomas are defined as papillary thyroid cancers less than 1 cm in size and are often found incidentally during surgery for benign thyroid conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk-stratification is an essential part of determining long-term follow up following surgical treatment of papillary thyroid carcinoma. The American Thyroid Association (ATA) defines \u201clow risk\u201d papillary thyroid carcinoma as having the following characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Intrathyroidal tumour \u0026lt;4cm in size, with absence of gross extrathyroidal extension/vascular invasion/aggressive histology subtypes\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Complete macroscopy tumour resection\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 No macroscopic locoregional or distant metastases\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u2019s papillary thyroid carcinoma is 1 cm in size, has been resected with clear surgical margins, and has no features of aggressive histology, it is categorised as low risk. The American Thyroid Association\u2019s recommended management for low risk papillary thyroid carcinoma is\u00a0biannual GP review for two years, then annually, as well as 12-24 monthly neck ultrasonography. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003Eneck ultrasound surveillance in 12 months \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient management for this patient. Thyroid microcarcinomas have an excellent prognosis with very low rates of recurrence (approximately 6% at 20 years and 9% at 40 years). Once the tumour has been completely removed, as in this case, the risk of recurrence or metastasis is minimal. Clinical surveillance typically involves regular thyroid function tests and physical examinations, however, it is recommended that ultrasound imaging should also be performed at regular intervals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI neck with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for routine follow-up of thyroid microcarcinoma. MRI is a more expensive and less accessible imaging modality that offers no advantage over ultrasound for thyroid cancer surveillance, particularly for low-risk disease such as microcarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompletion lymph node dissection\u003C/strong\u003E would be an unnecessarily aggressive approach for a microcarcinoma without evidence of lymph node involvement. Prophylactic lymph node dissection has not been shown to improve outcomes in patients with small, incidentally discovered papillary thyroid cancers and carries risks of surgical complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadioiodine ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for thyroid microcarcinomas. Multiple studies have demonstrated that radioiodine treatment does not improve recurrence rates or survival for patients with low-risk thyroid cancers, particularly microcarcinomas. The potential side effects of radioiodine (including salivary gland dysfunction, bone marrow suppression, and increased risk of secondary malignancies) outweigh any theoretical benefit in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid microcarcinoma (less than 1 cm) has an excellent prognosis with very low recurrence rates.","Radioiodine ablation is not indicated for thyroid microcarcinoma as it does not improve long-term outcomes."],"references":["Sherman SI. Thyroid carcinoma. Lancet. 2003 Feb 8;361(9356):501-11. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12583960/","Watson-Brown P, Anderson D. Differentiated thyroid cancer: A guide to survivorship care. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2023;52(1-2). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2023/january-february/differentiated-thyroid-cancer","Fields TD, Underwood HJ, Pitt SC. Management of Small Papillary Thyroid Cancers. Surg Clin N Am 104; 2024:725\u201340 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.suc.2024.02.003"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96592"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96592"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T21:08:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T21:10:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114589"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nul